03:52.636 --> 04:11.995
Of

03:52.636 --> 04:11.995
all your scholarly work, what one or two 
publications would you point to with greatest

03:52.636 --> 04:11.995
pride?

04:26.858 --> 04:32.704
My research was mainly diversified, very 
diversified. As I tell you, the one that I was most

04:32.724 --> 04:38.070
satisfied with was one of the horses, because we 
did define that. And it has an impact. We did some

04:42.195 --> 04:44.697
other things that I think were... This is the one 
about the, and the fence? Yes. Okay. Where did you

04:51.284 --> 04:52.866
publish that? Journal of American Medical 
Association, American Journal of Veterinary

04:54.331 --> 04:59.098
Research. And

05:01.061 --> 05:06.790
we had other publications on national disease. I 
did quite a bit on identifying new pathogens of

05:06.810 --> 05:17.506
fungi and worked with the National Institute of 
Health mycologists on those. And those were

05:18.708 --> 05:22.313
enjoyable because they new knowledge and the 
identification of new species, which have later

05:23.558 --> 05:30.086
been found in humans.

05:36.914 --> 05:47.528
Some of the others are, like I say, the one on the 
sheep has gotten less emphasis because sheep are

05:36.914 --> 05:47.528
just not that important anymore. And that's in 
some people's opinion. But

05:53.562 --> 06:16.052
I guess the thing that I've gotten satisfaction 
out of in my career has been my graduate program,

05:53.562 --> 06:16.052
which we had good people that came out and are 
well-represented.

06:17.774 --> 06:20.818
Which doctoral students would you point to with 
greatest pride?

06:26.587 --> 06:28.930
Well, I think Gary Adams is one. Ken Pierce.

06:37.759 --> 06:42.284
We had others like Gwynne Allman.

